div.div:
Speed/position interface structure graph
In between or outside of all these crazy theories which apply some interface structure, is the real structure, where some of these theories may other theories trivial (adjacent) and lead to other theories.

div.div:
Embedded Variable
Speed is embedded on position, so when one is measured/held constant, the other varies because it's foundation is being interacted with.

div.div:
Direct/Adjacent Dependent Variable
Speed is dependent on position, so they are causally adjacent and causally similar, which is like equivalence, in the form of an approximate equivalence.

Interim Variable
(plus Switching Function to switch variable position to find correct position)
Position is causally positioned between speed and momentum, so the more distant variable should be measured to avoid interacting with/changing the more adjacent variable in the causal sequence.

Position is an equivalent alternate to speed (they capture the same degree/ratio/type/structure of information, so they can be considered equivalent alternates).

Position is a variant of speed (they're the same variable, appearing in different structures)

Position and speed have a hidden variable (like an interface variable which standardizes and encapsulates both of them).

div.div:
Overlapping Variables (creating a mutual exclusivity)
Position and speed are like other variables where only one value can be selected at a time, as they overlap in some structure (like in their usage structure) to take up enough space or other resources that only one can be interacted with at a given time.

Vacillating Discrete Variables
Position and speed are discrete variables, which vacillate between each other.

div.div:
Mutually Exclusive Variables
Position and speed are mutually exclusive variables (position can't exist when speed exists, given that speed is a variable of change, the change rate, and position implies a static state, rather than a changing state)

div.div:
False Paradox
The paradox of position/speed only being measurable one at a time is a false paradox.
Paradox resolution structures involve structures like avoiding dichotomies/tradeoffs/other mutually exclusive structures, so handling the problem of 'changing the momentum of the particle during measurement' by offsetting it in some way to account for the change created by measurement is a way to integrate those falsely opposing structures.
